roduction dur\ning the year valued at $364,650,000, or\nabout nine times the Pennsylvania out-\nI put. Texas, with but 36,280 wells, was\nrm EVENING STAR, D. C., THURSDAY. OCTOBER 2. 1930.\ncredited with a total petroleum output\nf of 5322,520,000. California\u2019s bare 10,520\nwells operating during 1929 had an out\nput worth $321,367,000. California pro\nduction worked out to an average of 75\nbarrels per day per well; Oklahoma's\n11.3 barrels, and the Texas figure was\nslightly under 23. These three States\nrepresented four-fifths of the national\nproduction of crude, which the bureau\nannounced was worth $1,280,000,000.\nI September, October, November and\nr December mean seventh, eighth, ninth\ns and tenth months of the year, whereas\nthey are the ninth, tenth, eleventh and\ntwelfth. The cause of this error is the\nfact that the year used to begin with\ns the month of March.\nWET CONGRESS GAINS\nSLIGHT, SAYS McBRIDE\n\u201cProhibition Firmly Intrenched,\u201d\nDeclares Anti-Saloon League Head\non Arkansas Visit.\nBr the Associated Press.\nL LITTLE ROCK, Ark., October 2 \u2014Dr.\nF. Scott Mc\u00dfride, general superintendent\nof the Anti-Saloon League of America,\nI Tuesday expressed himself as \u201cwell\npleased\u201d with the prohibition situation\nin Arkansas, in the East and in Chica\ngo. where he once directed the League's\nactivities in Illinois.\nDr. Mc\u00dfride, here to confer with the\nState organization of the Anti-Saloon\nLeague, was not at all ruffled by the\nforensic furor raging over the issue in\nthe Eastern wet strongholds, but ad\nmitted that \u201cwe have been a bit over\nconfident\u201d\n\u201cProhibition in firmly Intrenched,\u201d\nthe prohibition leader said and dis\nmissed as \u201cunimportant\u201d the \u201cslight\ngains made by the wets\u201d in Congress In\nthe Fall campaigns.\n\u201cThe next Senate will be as dry as it\never was and there will be no more\nthan 10 supporters lost at the most in\nthe House.\n\u201cIt is significant,\u201d he went on, \u201cthat\nthe wets are afraid to face a return of\nthe saloon. In All their proposals fer\nmodification or repeal they Insist that\nthere be no return of the saloon. That,\nthen, is an admls\u00dfion on their part that\nconditions arc better under prohibition\nthan they were in the saloon days.\n*A great deal la made of the gang\nactivities 1q Chicago and other large\ncities.\n\u201cThe truth bf the matter is, the\nswigs have always been there, and have\nallied with the liquor Interests.\nProhibition has succeeded In bringing\nthem out. In making their activities\nknown to the country at large.\u201d\nMore than 0.000,000 acres In India\nare cultivated for rice.\nCHAIN STORE HEAD SEES\nPROSPERITY RETURNING\nBusiness Courage and Sane Retail\ning Factor, Says A. H. Morril,\nRe-Elected at Chicago.\nBy the Associated Press.\nCHICAGO. October 2.\u2014Confidence\nIn a gradual return of prosperity was\nexpressed yesterday by Albert H. Mor\nrill, Cincinnati, president of the Na\ntional Chain Store Association, at the\nfinal session of the association'4 con\nvention.\n\u201cActivities of the axsnHaHnn fno\n1 next 12 months will b: devoted to fur\nt therin\u00df tlr: interests of better retell\nronditienr. throubout tna country,.*\u2019 eeid\nMr. Morrill, who was re-elected pre6i\ndent of the association.\n\"Questions of commodity prictnc, re\ntail prices and control of overhead have\nbeen carefully considered In connection\nI with present economic mwmiwh-\nMeanwhUe compai ales, while net wnduly\noptimistic, are confident that business\ncourage and sane administration of re\ntaO operations will be an Immediate\nand permanent factor In prosperity.\u201d\nRay H. Ott of New York was elected\ntreasurer of the organlmtton.\nMore than 100,000 Russians have set\nr law Im IfAfeA AUtaaiA\nC-1","height":"25560","width":"19890"}}
